{
  "text": "Second, even if unilateral dichromats are (improbably) cyclopean bilateral dichromats, and so see the bilateral's colors with their dichromatic eye, the matching and description data are consistent with the Revised Reduction View. Unless very careful measures are taken to ensure that subjects only accept complete perceptual matches, the fact that a subject accepts a match between two stimuli does not establish that they are perceptually identical, only that they are similar in a salient respect (see, for example, [CITATION_1] ). If we suppose that yellowishness and unique yellow are saliently similar, then matching experiments pose no difficulty. And given that the unilateral dichromat just has normal color vocabulary to describe stimuli presented to his dichromatic eye, it is not surprising that 'yellow' and 'blue' are the words of choice.",
  "citation_candidates": [
